Instruction reduction and Binary size are correlated but not identical. Agressive inlining would ensure that the mutliple management instructions are removed from the IR, but this could involve copying the function contents mutliple times. 

An increased binary size would hurt if the the program doesn't fit in the L1 Instruction Cache (I-Cache). This will make the program run slower anyways because of instruction cache misses.

02. Break and Fix, instcombine

instcombine is a peephold optimizer which does a simple rearrangement. There could be another pass that would counter this and these two would then go back and forth, trying to fix the mess that the other creates.

03. Confusion for Branch Predictors

Branch prediction could break over agressive instruction folding, so much to the point where the natural flow for a program being executed by the CPU would break, and then this creates issues on its own.

04. SROA payoff with delayed returns

Goes from struct to variables. The problem lies with when SROA is applied, so the system will have to identify the optimal sequence to apply these things. That's a part of the phase-ordering problem.








